        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer352518943" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14953737357637115654">As a big fan of Christian fantasy, this book was pleasantly surprising. It&apos;s definitely not the YA high-action, low-dialogue fantasy that I was expecting. It&apos;s actually a lot deeper and meant for an older audience. <br/><p>The main character, Eldrin (renamed Abramm later on), is the fifth son of the king of Kiriath. As a child, he didn&apos;t excel in fencing, like his younger brother Gillard, because his love was in religion and history. He joined the religious group known as the Matatio at a young age, giv</p></span>
  <span id="freeText14953737357637115654" style="display:none">As a big fan of Christian fantasy, this book was pleasantly surprising. It's definitely not the YA high-action, low-dialogue fantasy that I was expecting. It's actually a lot deeper and meant for an older audience. <br /><p>The main character, Eldrin (renamed Abramm later on), is the fifth son of the king of Kiriath. As a child, he didn't excel in fencing, like his younger brother Gillard, because his love was in religion and history. He joined the religious group known as the Matatio at a young age, giving up his rights as a prince. <br /></p><p> At the beginning of the book, Eldrin is twenty-one and just about to take his final vows to become a full Brother and leave his past life behind him forever. When he gets to Kiriath, he discovers that the throne isn't so far away from him as it used to be, and his life turns upside-down. <br /></p><p>I'd recommend this to anyone 16+ who's looking for a good, epic Christian fantasy fix. This book stands pretty well on its own, and anyone who wants more can read the next three in the series as well.</p></span>
  <a data-text-id="14953737357637115654" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


