<div id="review_2723852716" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2723852716" />
    <a title="Kes" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70325177-kes"><img alt="Kes" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2723852716?book_show_action=true">Feb 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kes" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kes" href="/user/show/70325177-kes">Kes</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8228646-light-of-eidon">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70325177-kes?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70325177-kes?shelf=read-2019">read-2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2723852716" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11747436203436311185">This started off feeling rather Christian-inspired: we start with Eldrin, a novice of Eidon. Eidon is the god a monotheistic state religion, and he&apos;s associated with light, flames, being the defender of man, etc. Eidon stands in opposition to the Terstan religion, which marks its followers with a golden shieldmark. The religion of Eidon teaches that the Terstan adherents are associated with darkness etc.<br/><br/>Eldrin - known at birth as Abram - was the fifth in line to the throne; we start with him fin</span>
  <span id="freeText11747436203436311185" style="display:none">This started off feeling rather Christian-inspired: we start with Eldrin, a novice of Eidon. Eidon is the god a monotheistic state religion, and he's associated with light, flames, being the defender of man, etc. Eidon stands in opposition to the Terstan religion, which marks its followers with a golden shieldmark. The religion of Eidon teaches that the Terstan adherents are associated with darkness etc.<br /><br />Eldrin - known at birth as Abram - was the fifth in line to the throne; we start with him finding out that his father and older brothers have died. He is now second in line (with another brother behind him). This obviously creates consternation, as he renounced his titles before entering the priesthood. We then discover that there's a sinister plot afoot, resulting in Eldrin being shipped off to foreign lands as a slave. Eldrin then <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[becomes a gladiator in those foreign lands, improves his swordplay dramatically, and we end the book with him contributing to overthrowing the kingdom there and converting everyone to Terstan <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />There's an interesting mix of religion and magic that's not really explored in the first book. Faith appears to give special powers to their adherents (e.g. manifesting a shield, summoning demon birds). There are magics like illusions, or portals that link places together.<br /><br />The worldbuilding feels ok - it felt like a fantasy version of Christianity (there are ports, deserts and desert tribes, etc), and that wasn't my cup of tea. The plot line (someone weak becoming strong / discovering faith) was standard. It's not a bad book, just a boring one. Unfortunately, I'm not tempted to move on to the sequels.<br /><br />2/5 stars</span>
  <a data-text-id="11747436203436311185" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

