  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3632075019" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3632075019" />
    <a title="K L" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/77289651-k-l"><img alt="K L" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1521522587p2/77289651.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3632075019?book_show_action=true">Nov 06, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K L" class="user" itemprop="url" name="K L" href="/user/show/77289651-k-l">K L</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3632075019" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5319797892067471920">While I recommend this novel, I couldn&apos;t finish it quickly. I had a nagging frustration but couldn&apos;t quite place why or what it was. First off, it&apos;s difficult to tell where the story is going. Karen Hancock builds the plot slowly, and it spans years. I realized that&apos;s what problem was: <i>The Light of Eidon</i> feels like two books smashed into one. The complexity, which is the book&apos;s greatest strength, is also its Achilles Heel. <br/><br/>The world-building, for example, is phenomenal. The countries, customs, a</span>
  <span id="freeText5319797892067471920" style="display:none">While I recommend this novel, I couldn't finish it quickly. I had a nagging frustration but couldn't quite place why or what it was. First off, it's difficult to tell where the story is going. Karen Hancock builds the plot slowly, and it spans years. I realized that's what problem was: <i>The Light of Eidon</i> feels like two books smashed into one. The complexity, which is the book's greatest strength, is also its Achilles Heel. <br /><br />The world-building, for example, is phenomenal. The countries, customs, and languages all read like real places one could walk right into. However, the intricate details can also bog down the plot. OK, the harbor and billowing sails are beautiful, but the main character is in danger! <br /><br />The plot flows surprisingly smoothly for all the events and years Karen Hancock fit in-between 400 pages. Most authors couldn't have pulled it off. That being said, I read this book in small bite-sized chunks rather than racing through to the end; it was simply too much. As I said, the slow-burn plot is its both best and worst quality.<br /><br />Only several chapters into the second book in the series, I found it much better. The pacing issues in #1 are not as evident in #2. I've heard the books get better as they go on, and while I'm only halfway through the second installment, this seems to be true.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5319797892067471920" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

